  BlogPost(
    id: '1',
    title: 'All about clubs at IIT Ropar',
    summary: 'Explore the diverse range of cultural, technical, literary, and sports clubs at IIT Ropar, offering endless opportunities to learn, grow, and pursue your passions.',
    content:
        'After two or three years of intensive preparation for the JEE, you\'re likely weary of the routine of mock tests, assignments, and exams. I certainly felt that way after the JEE Advanced. Your dedication has earned you a place in the prestigious engineering institute, IIT Ropar. Now, it\'s time to broaden your horizons and immerse yourself in new experiences. Our institute boasts a multitude of clubs, offering a diverse array of activities. Each club is led by a dedicated team of students, including the Secretary, Mentors, Representatives, and Coordinators, who are eager to facilitate your learning and exploration. Beginning with Cultural clubs which comes under the Board of cultural Affairs (BOCA). There are numerous clubs to help you explore your passions and hobbies beyond academics. D-cypher, the dance club, offers a variety of dance forms including western, bhangra, and classical, so you can move to the rhythm of your choice. Alankar, the music club, invites you to let your soul dance to the beats of any instrument you desire. If you have a flair for acting, Undekha, the dramatics club, is the perfect place for you to shine in plays and naataks. Arturo, the photography club, is ideal for those who love capturing moments, offering endless inspiration for budding photographers. Vibgyor, the fine arts club, is a haven for artists and painting enthusiasts, providing a canvas for your creativity. Lastly, Epicure, the cooking club, is perfect for foodies and culinary enthusiasts, where you can indulge in cooking and savor the taste of creativity. Join us and make the most of these vibrant clubs! Moving onto to our Technical clubs which comes under the Board of science and Technology (BOST) We offer a diverse array of clubs to fuel your interests and passions. The Coding Club is perfect for those who are passionate about competitive programming and DSA, providing the ultimate challenge for your skills. For aspiring software developers, SoftCom, the Software Community, opens a world of coding, innovation, and endless possibilities. The Robotics Club awaits those who love tinkering and building, while the Aeromodelling Club offers hands-on experience in designing, building, and flying model aircraft for aviation enthusiasts. If cars and EVs fascinate you, the Automotive Club is the ideal place to expand your knowledge. FinCom, the Finance Club, caters to those inclined towards finance and economics. The Computer Integrated Manufacturing (CIM) Club is dedicated for those who are interested in turning their ideas into reality using CAD, and exploring automation in manufacturing. Unleash your digital creativity in Monochrome, the Graphic Designing Club. If AI and ML excite you, the Iota Cluster is the perfect beginning. Lastly, Zenith, the Astronomy Club, is your launchpad to exploring the mysteries of space. Join these clubs and embark on an exciting journey of discovery and learning! Moving forward we have Literary clubs Which comes under the Board of Literary Affairs (BOLA) Variety of clubs are available to enhance your skills and explore new interests. Enarrators, the oratory club, helps you become more confident and eloquent, eliminating any stage fright. Debsoc, the debating club, offers lively discussions to sharpen your argumentative skills and boost your confidence. Enigma, the quizzing club, features brain-teasing quizzes and thrilling trivia nights, providing something for everyone. Alfaaz is a supportive community for both seasoned poets and beginners, offering endless inspiration. Alpha Productions, the filmmaking and video editing club, is the perfect place to uplift your video editing skills. Filmski invites you into the world of cinematic wonders, igniting your passion for movies, anime, and web series. Lastly, the Model United Nations (MuN) club is ideal for those interested in learning more about the United Nations. Join these clubs and expand your horizons! Besides these, we also have Sports clubs which comes under the Board of Sports Affairs (BOSA) Our Institute offers a wide range of sports facilities Outdoor sports as well as the indoor activities which includes Athletics, Badminton, Basketball, Cricket, Football, Hockey, Lawn Tennis, Volleyball, Chess, Table Tennis, Weightlifting and Gym facilities. All in all, you will get to learn many new things and a lot to enjoy at the same time with the vibrant clubs flourishing in the campus! Hoping to see you all to participate with full enthusiasm in the club activities and events!',
    author: 'Anonymous',
    date: 'June 2, 2026',
    readMinutes: 5,
    tag: BlogTag.club,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '2',
    title: 'Fresher\'s Guide',
    summary: 'A comprehensive guide for freshers covering hostel allotments, necessary purchases, campus facilities, and general advice to navigate early days at IIT Ropar.',
    content:
        'IMPORTANT NOTES: Hostel rooms will be allotted on first come first serve basis. Hostels are well equipped with LAN and Wi-Fi. You will not be able to access them immediately but you can, in a day or two after you get user id and password from IT section at IIT Ropar. Register yourself with library as early as possible as it will be the sole source for your initial study. Get your bonafide certificates from the academic section on first or very next day as it will help you to get a new mobile connection and a bank account at IIT Ropar branch of SBI Get yourself an account at SBI branch IIT Ropar asap, as it will be the only account you can handle easily and easily access from the campus itself for your stay in campus. Get in touch with your seniors asap as they will be a handy source to guide you well for remaining rest of your 4 years Necessary Things to buy for hostels: Scientific Calculator – fx 991 ES (preferably) or Fx 991-MS. You will require this more than your books for next four years. So it is better to buy it from home only. A well conditioned medium size college bag. Forget about all the movie stuffs you will have to carry much more here. In later stages laptop will be the thing you will be carrying the most. Bedsheets .But no special need of buying daily stuff like bucket, mug and matteresses from home as they will be available to buy inside the campus on the day of registration. Also it is good to buy from there only. Some locks and keys as you will have to lock your luggage on the first day as it will be very busy . After that it will be ok … Facilities inside and around campus: Cafeteria inside the campus generally open from 8 in the morning to 12 in the night. Also there is a Juice Corner in Utility Block. Laundary services are available within the hostels. You just have to give Rs15 for 10 clothes and you are done. Giving your own detergent is optional. One stationary shop inside campus. Geysers are available inside the hostels 24 hrs. Believe it most of us use only once a week in winters In initial stages laptop will not be necessary as you will be having computer labs and that will be sufficient. Also laptop at such a starting stage gets you neglect your study more….its just a general experience!',
    author: 'ISMP Team',
    date: 'Jul 25, 2019',
    readMinutes: 3,
    tag: BlogTag.campus,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '3',
    title: 'Importance of group studies in college',
    summary: 'Discover the benefits of group studying, from gaining diverse perspectives and improving communication skills to staying motivated and building a balanced study routine.',
    content:
        'Entering college marks the beginning of a thrilling journey filled with academic challenges, new friendships, and unforgettable experiences. One of the key aspects of college and hostel life that can significantly enhance our learning experience is group study. When you study in a group, you\'re exposed to different viewpoints and approaches to solving problems. Each member of the group brings their unique understanding and insights, which can help you grasp complex concepts more easily. Working together on challenging problems can lead to more effective solutions. Explaining your ideas and listening to others helps improve your ability to articulate thoughts and understand different perspectives. These communication skills are invaluable in academic, professional, and personal life. You learn to work effectively with others and handle conflicts constructively. It\'s easy to procrastinate when studying alone, which I often used to do. However, being part of a study group encourages consistency. Regular group meetings create a structured study routine, helping you stay on track with your coursework. When you\'re feeling demotivated or stressed, your group members can offer encouragement and help you stay focused. This mutual support can be crucial, especially during exam periods. Sharing the workload, having group discussions, and sometimes just having a laugh can make studying a more pleasant experience. Teaching a concept to someone else is often the best way to learn it thoroughly. When studying alone, you might get stuck on difficult topics without immediate help. In a group, you can quickly clarify doubts and misunderstandings. College can be demanding, and it\'s easy to get isolated with your studies. Group study sessions provide an opportunity for social interaction, making your study routine more balanced and fulfilling.',
    author: 'Sukriti Bhandari (2023 Batch Mathematics and Computing)',
    date: 'Sep 15, 2021',
    readMinutes: 2,
    tag: BlogTag.academic,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '4',
    title: 'How to make decisions?',
    summary: 'A thoughtful guide on navigating hostel life, managing freedom responsibly, balancing academics with co-curriculars, and choosing the right peer group for personal growth.',
    content:
        'Leaving homes and stepping into the hostel for the next four years, will be a huge turning point in your life. So friends, why not turn in the right direction, for you have miles to go ahead? The good thing about hostels is freedom. The bad thing about them is, again, freedom. Once you are not answerable to anyone, you have the urge, the guts, and the capability to live life on your own terms. So, does that mean you have to carry the weight of all your responsibilities on your shoulders? Maybe. \'Maybe\', because it\'s one\'s own choice to either turn away from responsibilities and live a smooth but sedentary life, or to face them and grow as an individual. It\'s one\'s own decision-making that helps him steer his way through the tough times. And trust me, it is this decision-making skill that gives an \'extra\' to the ordinary. Neither a flip of a magic hat, nor a swoosh of a magic wand can inculcate in you this skill. One needs time and experience to acquire this skill. There are situations, some topsy-turvy times, when you might not be able to interpret as to what should be done at the given moment. At times, you might be missing out on things due to some other commitments. It is here, that your aforementioned skill comes into play. You just have to sort out your priorities according to your future goals, keeping your academics first, and then your co-curriculars. Generally, in the first few months of college life, one is zealous and keen to try out different clubs and become a part of different societies, which is good, if he/she knows how to manage time well. But, what happens is, things don\'t turn out the way we plan. Amidst all the excitement and enthusiasm, one starts to lose focus and the work starts piling up. One should always keep in mind, his goal, and shouldn\'t let his focus deviate. All the decisions should be made while keeping his short-term as well as long-term goals as priority. I sincerely encourage you to join clubs, but not too many as your academics might get affected. Also know one thing, friends, solely academics will take you nowhere. Clubs and societies develop one\'s personality. Our college provides an ocean of opportunities, one just needs to dive in and explore. Decision making is also very important when it comes to choosing your friend circle. You might have heard a phrase “You are the average of your friends”. One’s peer group affects one’s personality drastically. One needs to be careful while choosing friends. It is your peer group that will either encourage you on your way to success or will try to pull you down the ladder to your goal. Not everyone can be expected to understand you in a manner to be qualified as your closest friend, but apart from having a few friends close, be on good terms with others too as you never know when you might need someone. Friendships and bonds made during the hostel life remain forever, so this is a huge area to invest in, wisely. It is advisable for the freshers to have a healthy interaction with their seniors, who are always there to guide them in case of any issue.',
    author: 'Anonymous',
    date: 'Aug 20, 2019',
    readMinutes: 4,
    tag: BlogTag.academic,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '5',
    title: 'Inter year interactions',
    summary: 'An insightful overview of interacting with seniors and batchmates, highlighting how these connections help you survive and thrive during your college journey.',
    content:
        'INTER-YEAR INTERACTIONS! Hey there! I am a 2nd-year undergrad student from the chemical department, IIT Ropar. Furthermore, being on campus for six months or so, I\'ve socialized with loads and loads of seniors from all year and every branch you can think of, owing to the beautiful culture of interaction the institute offers. Being completely blunt, interactions with peeps will make you survive here and enjoy your journey to the fullest. Let us start with your batchmates, the 1st year. It is obvious you\'re definitely going to interact with them the most. You will all have the same classes, labs, clubs, and whatnot! My advice will be to talk to (or at least try to) as many peeps as you can at the start, remember, this is not just about making friends; it is also about making connections that will help you in the future. You do not have to go the extra mile to talk to them, they all are as new as you are. Go on, start with a smile and a hi! Skipping on to the seniors! The part which makes your spine tickle. I\'ve seen students being hesitant (dare I say, scared) to approach seniors, which I find absurd because seniors are the most important part of your institute. Stepping onto the campus, with a confused and overwhelmed look, you first meet your mentor (a 2nd-year student from your branch), who helps you in and around the campus. Transitioning from a JEE life into college life isn\'t easy to handle, but your mentor makes it smoother. Anyways, the second-yearites are the ones who\'re managing the clubs. They are the ones who\'ll guide you about the little intricacies of college life since they\'re the ones who were in your shoes just a couple of months earlier. Many of them have started to find their footing in various specializations, from academics to arts, and you will always find someone willing to guide you in anything that interests you. This is the year you will be the closest with, try to get out of your comfort circle and talk to them. Not going to lie, I have a better friendship with a couple of seniors than I have with my batchmates! Coming to the third year, this is the year which you\'ll probably get to see the least of, but also the one you should probably get the most inspired by. With internship season right on their heads coupled with a ginormous academic load, they have chosen their fields of specialization and are working to be masters in them. Also, being in the college for two years, they are well versed in the administrative and academic structure of the college, and therefore the student council, as well as the mentors for all the clubs, are usually from this year. Don\'t keep the 3rd year peeps aloof, you\'re sure to learn a lot from them. Next, the fourth yearites! Determined and busy, since placement season is on, they\'re the ones who\'ll make you realize the value of college life since they\'re at the end of it. They have the most peculiar anecdotes and the best perspective of life since they know what sticks even after college and what is just momentary. The fourth year watches your batch with fondness because they see their past in you. MTech and Ph.D. interactions are also one of the most crucial ones since they\'re your TAs as well friends if you seem to share any common interests. Since many of them are from different colleges, they share experiences of different places with you. Summing up, inter-year interactions are one of the most memorable things about your college life. You\'ll learn from them, have fun with them, sometimes get reprimanded, and sometimes get appreciated by them. It\'s a cycle that goes on since your seniors will enrich you with their experiences, and you\'ll do the same to your juniors. Ultimately, you will find yourself in a special bond with them. All I would like to say is don\'t leave a blank spot in your canvas painted with memories :)',
    author: '2nd-year undergrad student',
    date: 'Jan 10, 2021',
    readMinutes: 4,
    tag: BlogTag.campus,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '6',
    title: 'Institute Student Mentorship Programme',
    summary: 'An introduction to the ISMP, outlining how senior mentors will assist and guide incoming freshers through academics, extracurriculars, and personal life.',
    content:
        'Congratulations on making it to IIT Ropar, where you’ll spend some of the best times of your life. You’ve probably received loads of congratulations on your success in JEE. Let us add ours to this pile. Now down to business about the Student Mentorship Program.As you pack your bags for IIT Ropar, there are likely to be a lot of questions on your mind about your future life here. We have tried to answer many of these here. Many new questions will emerge as you maneuver around the labyrinth of processes and procedures, courses and activities at IIT. This is where your mentor comes in. IIT Ropar will strive to assist your upcoming journey. The journey, where you not only aim about emplacement but also add a lot of escapades in your life. Of course, there will be obstacles which you need to hurdle upon. This is where we think the experiences of your next higher students comes into play to mentor you.The Institute Student Mentorship Program (ISMP), is a program within the IIT Ropar, with the primary objective to enable constructive and positive interaction, guidance and mentorship of junior students by senior students. The vision is to inculcate right attitude from beginning and sustain an environment that promotes personal growth and participation in creation of tender community. For this purpose, the ISMP carefully selects mentors from amongst senior students at IIT Ropar-someone that you can approach with queries on any issue like academics, extracurricular, personal life or the issue of maintaining a balance between them. They will be your friends, philosophers and guides through your exciting journey in IIT Ropar. We will try to ensure that each individual’s personal and academic life is hassle free while his/her stay in IIT Ropar .We will keep in touch with you all through out the year, interacting and learning from you about your experiences through this system. Wishing you good luck for your stay at IIT Ropar.',
    author: 'ISMP Team',
    date: 'Jul 15, 2019',
    readMinutes: 2,
    tag: BlogTag.academic,
  ),
  BlogPost(
    id: '7',
    title: 'Managing Social Life and Academics',
    summary: 'A realistic look at the challenges of balancing academics and social life at IIT, with tips on time management, making friends, and prioritizing effectively without burning out.',
    content:
        'Managing academics and social life Life at IIT is not as glamorous as it may seem from the outside. The relentless stream of weekly assignments, quizzes, midterms, and finals keeps students perpetually on their toes. Alongside these academic demands, carving out time for coding or pursuing personal passions becomes a formidable challenge. This reality is often overlooked by those who haven\'t experienced it. However, let\'s be honest: within IIT, there are two main types of students, “the disciplined ones” and “the all-nighters.” The disciplined ones complete their daily tasks, revise lectures, and get a good night\'s sleep before exams. Conversely, the all-nighters cram the night before exams yet still manage to score comparably, if not higher, than their more disciplined peers. Your first task upon entering IIT is to identify which category you belong to. Once you do, navigating your path forward will be much easier. At IIT, it is essential to transition out of the intense “JEE phase,” interact with people, and make friends who can support you in this new environment, far from home. Fun and relaxation are crucial components of a balanced life. Some students try to schedule every minute for studying, but this often leads to inefficient use of time. Overworking can result in diminishing returns, where longer study hours yield progressively less productivity. Freshmen often struggle to balance academics and social life, so here are some tips to help you achieve that balance. Firstly, assign specific time slots to your daily tasks. After dinner is an excellent time for socializing since everyone is generally free from classes and out on “night strolls” at that hour. However, remember your ultimate goal: do not stay out all night socializing and then sleep through your lectures or study sessions. Joining a club that aligns with your interests is another great way to maintain balance. At IIT Ropar, we have numerous clubs managed by dedicated seniors. Participating in club activities allows you to pursue your passions and increase your skill while meeting people with similar interests. Additionally, being active during festivals and other event preparations can help you build a network of valuable contacts which increases your social skill. In conclusion, college life is the first significant step towards adulthood. For many of us, this is the first time we live away from the protective shell of our families. To avoid feeling lonely or depressed, it is crucial to establish a supportive social circle. Set your priorities and work diligently towards them. Do not fear making mistakes; these experiences will help you learn and grow. This is what IIT life is about: continually evolving into a better version of yourself. Wishing you the very best on your journey ahead, freshers.',
    author: 'Anonymous',
    date: 'Sep 5, 2019',
    readMinutes: 3,
    tag: BlogTag.academic,
  ),
  BlogPost(
